## 4. Cash and Payment Security

### 4.1 Cash Handling

- Limit cash kept in the register at any time to a working float defined by the owner (e.g., $200 maximum).
- Conduct cash drops to a safe throughout the day when the register exceeds the defined float.
- Two employees should be present during opening cash counts and closing cash reconciliation where possible.
- Cash must never be left unattended in an unsecured area.

### 4.2 Safe

- A commercial-grade, bolted-down safe must be used for cash storage.
- Only the owner and designated manager(s) have the safe combination.
- Safe combinations must be changed if access is compromised or an authorized employee departs.

### 4.3 Bank Deposits

- Deposits should be made daily or on a regular schedule; never accumulate more than two days of receipts.
- Vary the time and route of bank deposits to avoid predictable patterns.
- A single employee should not make deposits alone if carrying significant cash. Use a second employee or a cash courier service if amounts are substantial.

### 4.4 Card Payments

- Use a PCI DSS-compliant point-of-sale (POS) system.
- Do not store customer payment card data in paper or digital form beyond transaction completion.
- Card terminals must be physically secured to the counter and inspected regularly for evidence of tampering or skimming devices.
- Report any suspected card terminal tampering to the POS vendor and relevant card networks immediately.

